article.description: Yolanda Griffith had 20 points and eight rebounds, helping the Sacramento Monarchs to a 71-62 victory over the Indiana Fever on Sunday night.
article.headline: Griffith scores 20; Monarchs win 3-of-4
article.linkText: Bolton's late 3 guides Monarchs past Fever
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Sacramento Monarchs' strong inside
game and a long road trip combined to wear down the Indiana Fever.

Yolanda Griffith had 20 points and eight rebounds, helping the
Monarchs to a 71-62 victory over struggling Indiana on Sunday.

Tangela Smith scored 16 points and DeMya Walker had 10 for the
Monarchs. Led by Griffith at center, Sacramento's inside players
combined to make 18 of 31 shots. They also had 12 assists.

"They are long and as athletic as anyone in the league, they
are good players," Indiana coach Brian Winters said.

Indiana dropped its fourth straight game, all on the road in the
last week. The Fever have lost six consecutive road games overall,
tying a franchise record.

Natalie Williams had 17 points and eight rebounds for the Fever,
who were 21-for-24 on 3-point attempts. Tamika Catchings made three
3-pointers and had 15 points, while Kelly Schumacher added 12.

Griffith had four assists and three blocked shots for the
Monarchs, who made eight straight free throws in the final 40
seconds to secure the victory.

"We knocked down the free throws when we needed to," Griffith
said. "We felt comfortable at the end of the game, we didn't
panic."

Ruthie Bolton made a 3-point shot with 4:54 remaining that put
the Monarchs ahead 57-56. Sacramento never trailed again, winning
for the third time in four games.

"We played pretty well for the most part, but we made mistakes
at the end of the game," Winters said. "They made the plays and
we didn't down the stretch."

Trailing by 11 points early in the second half, the inside play
of Williams helped the Fever go on a 19-4 run and take a 54-50 lead
with 7:55 remaining.

Smith scored eight first-half points for the Monarchs, who used
a late run to take a 34-30 lead into halftime.

Catchings made two 3-pointers and scored 12 points in the first
half.
